Merge pull request #21626 from oscarbenjamin/pr_matrix_domainmatrix

Make Matrix use DomainMatrix internally

Guard against the *input* being non-hashable in the cache

The previous code assumed any TypeError was a hashing problem, meaning it
would run the code twice when that happened. The code in the caching is based
around the output needing to be hashable, but this is incorrect (I haven't
fixed that yet). This commit is primarly to see if this leads to any test
failures.

Don't try to guard against non-hashable results in the cache

See https://github.com/sympy/sympy/pull/21619#issuecomment-889540868. This can
cause issues when the function itself raises TypeError. Really, if a function
has the cacheit decorator and returns a non-hashable result, that is a bug.
Either the function should be fixed to return a hashable result, or some lower
level function that does always return hashable results should be cached
instead.

This commit is to see what sorts of tests will fail when this change is made.
We may also want to run the test suite in random order to try to find
failures, since that can affect caching.

feat(core): make sympy.Integer compatible with Integral ABC

Make `sympy.Integer` compatible with the `numbers.Integral` ABC as defined
in PEPs 3141 and 238. (See also PEP 239.) The necessary bitwise operations
(e.g. `1 << 2`) are added to `sympy.Integer` and `sympy.Integer` is
registered with the `Integral` ABC such that:

    isinstance(sympify(1), Integral) -> True

Prior to this commit, `sympy.Integer.__truediv__` and
`sympy.Integer.__rtruediv__` already returned `sympy.Rational` values,
which is not only ergonomic, but also appears compliant.

Make sinc(x).diff(x) not return a Piecewise

Currently, Piecewise.diff() is wrong for pointwise removable singularities.
This lead to sinc(x).diff(x, x) being wrong at x = 0. See
https://github.com/sympy/sympy/issues/11402.

The issue with Piecewise is difficult to solve, but we can work around sinc()
specifically by just returning cos(x)/x - sin(x)/x**2 for sinc(x).diff(x)
rather than a Piecewise. The value of the derivatives of sinc at 0 will have
to be evaluated with limit(), but this is preferable to having an incorrect
answer.

fix(polys): use DDM instead of Matrix for linsolve with RR/CC

Adds partial pivoting to DDM.rref and uses DDM.rref in linsolve for the
RR and CC domains. This is to avoid the problems with sdm_rref which
does not have adequate pivoting to handle numeric instability.

perf(polys): make EX faster for trivial operations

This commit avoids calls to cancel for some trivial operations in the EX
domain. This can lead to a big speed up for some integrals. For example

z1, z2 = symbols('z1, z2')
I = Integral(exp(-0.5*(((-1/z1)+1.39)**2+((-1/z2)+1.23)**2))*(1/(z1**2))*(1/(z2**2)),(z1,0,1),(z2,0,1))
I.doit()

In this case the integral is not computed with or without this change
but heurisch completes much faster with the change reducing the overall
time by 50%. Previously most of the time was spent in trivial calls to
cancel like cancel(0), cancel(3), etc.

revert expr_free_symbols

This is a general property that was added to solve a very
specific problem but it adds a layer of abstraction that is
not necessary in general.

1. objects that have structural "non-expression" nodes already
   allow one to focus on on the expression node if desired, e.g.

   >>> Derivative(f(x), x).expr
   f(x)

   introduction of this property encourages imprecise thinking
   when requesting free_symbols since it allows one to get
   symbols from a specific node of an object without specifying
   the node

2. it incorrectly added the property to AtomicExpr so numbers
   are returned as expr_free_symbols

   >>> S(2).expr_free_symbols
   2

3. the application of the concept was misapplied to define
   Subs.expr_free_symbols: it added in expr_free_symbols of
   the point but the point is a Tuple so nothing was added

functions: Implemented an _eval_expand_trig method for tanh

expand_trig now works to expand tanh. tanh(coeff*x) will be
expanded to coeff*tanh(x). Additionally, tanh now detects
double and half angle formulas, so if coeff is 2 or .5,
it will be epanded into the formulas below.

tanh half angle formula:
tanh(.5*x) = (cosh(x)-1)/sinh(x)

tanh double angle formula:
tanh(2x) = 2*tanh(x)/(1+tanh^2(x))

Finally _eval_expand_trig also expands tanh(x+y) using the
sum of arguments identity below.

tanh(x+y) = (tanh(x)+tanh(y))/(1+tanh(x)*tanh(y))

Example:

>>> from sympy import *
>>> x = Symbol('x')
>>> y = Symbol('y')

>>> expand_trig(tanh(x + y))
(tanh(x) + tanh(y))/(tanh(x)*tanh(y) + 1)

>>> expand_trig(tanh(2*x))
2*tanh(x)/(tanh(x)**2 + 1)

>>> expand_trig(tanh(3*x))
3*tanh(x)

>>> expand_trig(tanh(y*x))
tanh(x*y)

>>> expand_trig(tanh((1/2)*x))
(cosh(x) - 1)/sinh(x)

refactor(polys): move gmpy handling code to sympy.external

This commit moves the PythonRational class to a new sympy.external.gmpy
module. The new class PythonMPQ is defined to be compatible with gmpy2's
mpq type. This commit also drops support for integrating with gmpy
(1.x) since gmpy2 was released 10 years ago at this time.

It is now possible to do
   from sympy.external.gmpy import MPQ
which will give either PythonMPQ or gmpy's mpq type. A number of other
functions from gmpy2 have been moved into the sympy.external.gmpy
compatibility module so that they can be reused in other places. This
should make it possible to eliminate many of the polys domains that have
multiple versions for when gmpy is or is not installed.

This commit removes the previously introduced `legacy` option in the `get_segments` methods
and introduced the `get_data` method.

which is used by Matplotlib in order to apply color-gradients to the lines.

make symbolic Range canonical

Range tries to be as lenient as possible in accepting symbolic limits
but must then be careful to make no assumptions when being asked
for elements of that Range.

e.g. Range(x,x+5)[0] is not x unless we know that x is an integer;
we also do not know that the size is 5 unless we know if x is an
integer. If x == oo then this would be a null range.

Plotting - Improved custom labelling

As mentioned in issue 21300, the procedure to set custom labels to the expressions being plotted
was tedious. This commit add a new optional parameter to the plot interface, allowing to quickly
set custom labels to the expressions being plotted. For example, we can now write:

```
var("x, y")
plot((cos(x), "$f_{1}$"), (sin(x), (x, -2, 2), "f2"), (x / 10, (x, -6, 6)), legend=True)
```

Here, the first expression will be plotted over the default range `(x, -10, 10)` and will have a
label containing Latex code. The second expression will be plotted over the custom range
`(x, -2, 2)` having a string label. The last expression will be plotted over the custom range
`(x, -6, 6)` having the default label set to its string representation.

Back-compatibility has been an important thing to maintain. However, a few adjustments had to be
done. For example, previously it was possible to set the label of a single expression with the
`label` keyword:

```
plot(sin(x), label="test", legend=True)
```

With this commit, that keyword has been phased out (it doesn't do anything anymore, look at the
`_remove_label_key` function), and the docstrings has been updated with all the necessary
informations to correctly set custom labels.

From an implementation point of view, the old `check_arguments` function has been deprecated:
it was easier to come up with my own implementation in order to accomodate the new custom label
option, which can be found in the `_check_arguments` function. The latter has the same signature
of the former, and returns objects in the same format (with the added label string). Quite a few
tests have been implemented to make sure the new function produces the expected results.

All plot functions are going to sympify the provided arguments. However, when attempting to
sympify a string, it would either return an object of type Symbol, or it would raise an error
if any strange characters are present (/, {, }, $, ...). In order to solve this problem I had to
implement the `_plot_sympify` function, which is going to recursively sympify the provided
arguments, excluding the strings.

feat(assumptions) : Enhance Q.eq and Q.ne

Fix code quality

Include the transformed code in the error message if the eval in parse_expr() fails

This makes it clearer what is going on if a transformer causes some issue in
parse_expr. Even if the error is unrelated to a transformation, it is clearer,
because the line of code from eval_expr() is not otherwise shown in the
traceback.

Don't try to parse methods as implicit multiplications in parse_expr

For example x.y(z) should not be parsed as x.y*z.

Attributes of an object are almost never expressions that would be multiplied.
Methods are far more likely. Unlike for top-level names, we can't easily guess
what methods an object will have since we don't know its type, so we just
disable all implicit multiplications if the first name is a method.

Fixes #21020.

feat(polys): make FiniteExtension a proper domain

Allow division of an ExtensionElement over a ring but only where the
divisor is an invertible constant (unit) of the ground domain.

For example in QQ[y][x]/(x**2 - 2) we can divide by any nonzero element
of QQ (the units of QQ[y]). In ZZ[x]/(x**2 - 2) we can only divide by 1
or -1.

If the ground domain for a FiniteExtension is a field then it is assumed
that the extension is also a field although this might not hold if the
quotient polynomial is not irreducible (this is not checked). If the
ground domain is a field then division by any nonzero element is
allowed.

This applies in particular to nested extensions e.g.:
  K = QQ[x]/(x**2 - 2)[y]/(y**2 - x)
Here the ground domain is QQ[x]/(x**2 - 2) which is assumed to be a
field because QQ is. It is therefore assumed that K is a field as well.
Division by any nonzero element of K is then permitted and considered
exact so that f % g is always zero.

20519: symbols: faster creation of functions sharing parameters

If several functions share the same arguments, it is currently awkward (too long) to create them all.
Here is a proposal to construct them at once as in (note that cls=Function is not needed anymore):
It uses an additional option 'function_of'

>>> x,y,t = symbols('x,y,t')
>>> symbols('f,g,h', function_of=t)
(f(t), g(t), h(t))
>>> symbols('f,g,h', function_of=(x,y))
(f(x,y), g(x,y), h(x,y))
